<h4 id="scheme">Scheme</h4>
<ol>
  <li>How does it relate to probability distribution.</li>
  <li>How to recognize this equivalence.</li>
</ol>

<h4 id="definition">Definition</h4>
<p>Let $ \mathbb{G}<em>{1}=\left(\mathrm{V}, \mathrm{E}</em>{1}\right) $ and $
\mathbb{G}<em>{1}=\left(\mathrm{V}, \mathrm{E}</em>{2}\right) $ be two DAGs containing
the same set of variables V. Then $\mathbb{G_1}$ and $\mathbb{G_2}$ are called
Markov equivalent if for every three mutually disjoint subsets $A,B,C \subseteq
V$, $A$ and $B$ are d-separated by $C$ in $\mathbb{G}_1$ if and only if A and B
are d-separated by $C$ in $\mathbb{G}_2$.</p>

<h5 id="criterion">Criterion</h5>
<p>Two DAGs $\mathbb{G}_1$ and $\mathbb{G}_2$ are Markov equivalent if and only if
they have the same links(edges without regard for direction) and the same set of
uncoupled head-to-head meetings.</p>

<h4 id="dag-pattern">DAG pattern</h4>
<p>Let gp be a DAG pattern whose nodes are the elements of $V$, and A, B, and C be
mutually disjoint subsets of V. We say A and B are d-separated by C in gp if A
and B are d-separated by C in any DAG G in the Markov equivalence class
represnted by gp.</p>

